    <title>Combined summary - Off-chain transactions and miner fees</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T19:10:08.513696+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010101.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Lightning Network has introduced a new way for nodes to earn fees that were previously unavailable to Bitcoin miners due to the limitations of the base Bitcoin layer. However, there is a debate on whether off-chain transactions are favorable due to limited space and potential higher fees due to competition. While Lightning nodes can attach large fees to Bitcoin settlement transactions when they settle on the blockchain, this may not be beneficial in the long run as it could harm the security of the network.In an email conversation posted on August 10, 2015, between Hector Chu and Anthony Towns via the Bitcoin-dev mailing list, the time value of bitcoin was discussed. Chu argued that one could sell their Bitcoin for fiat and hold it for interest, while Towns countered that this only works if the interest rate on the fiat account is greater than the price rise in Bitcoin over the same term. The debate over off-chain transactions in Bitcoin has raised concerns about the impact on mining rewards, as without off-chain transactions, there is a paradox within a viable fee market as high-value transactions are willing to pay higher fees, and this could crowd out low-value transactions on-chain. Lightning significantly mitigates this problem by aggregating the low-value transactions off-chain. The Lightning Network raises the value of a transaction on the blockchain and enables nodes to collect their earned fees over time by settling on the blockchain. Nodes can attach higher fees to the Bitcoin settlement transaction and ensure their transactions get into the blockchain quickly. However, there is concern that off-chain transactions like Lightning could potentially extract fees that would otherwise be paid to miners if the transactions were on-chain.In a discussion among Bitcoin developers in 2015, the topic of users being willing to pay 100 times the fees of traditional transactions for the same limited space in a blockchain was raised. Some participants argued that paying for something you do not need and paying because you have money is not a good business strategy. It is crucial to consider the implications of off-chain transactions and their impact on miner rewards and network security, especially as rival payment networks compete for fees based on the duration and cost to process transactions.If Bitcoin's fees remain low and zero-conf transactions are possible, unique features will be required for rival payment networks to survive and make money for their investors. Closing less profitable channels in the Lightning Network is valuable as channel profitability varies over time and funds can be used elsewhere. Lightning transactions require payment for several things, including blockchain fees for opening/closing the channel, the time value of the funds being used to keep the channels open, and the maintenance costs of the hardware/software to run a lightning channel.</summary>
